        "excerpt": "Inasmuch as I exalted you from the dust and made you leader over My people Israel, and you have walked in the way of Jeroboam and have made My people Israel sin…",
        "body": "The opening oracle against Baasha (vv.1-4) is a near-verbatim repetition of the oracle against Jeroboam in 14:7-11 — the same raising 'from the dust,' the same verb 'made you leader' (nagid), the same fate for the household (dogs in the city, birds in the field). This literary echo is deliberate. Baasha was the instrument God used to fulfill the judgment against Jeroboam's house (15:29), yet Baasha then imitated the very sin that condemned the house he destroyed. The pattern is one of the most sobering in the entire Old Testament: God can use a sinful man to execute judgment on another sinful man, and then judge the instrument for the same sin. The instrument of wrath is not exempt from wrath.\n\nVerse 7 intensifies this by noting that the word came against Baasha 'both because of all the evil which he did... and because he struck it' — i.e., because he destroyed Jeroboam's house. Some interpreters have found this troubling: was Baasha being punished for obeying God's earlier word? The resolution lies in motive and manner. Baasha slaughtered Jeroboam's house not in obedience to God but in the exercise of dynastic ambition — the same ambition that drove him to adopt Jeroboam's idolatry afterward. God's sovereignty operates through human agents without sanctifying those agents' motives. The parallel with Jehu son of Nimshi (2 Kings 10:30-31) is instructive: God commended Jehu for executing the Omride dynasty and yet later punished the bloodshed of Jezreel (Hosea 1:4). The moral complexity is not contradiction; it is the consistent teaching that God governs history without authorizing every means used by those He governs.\n\nThe prophetic messenger here is Jehu son of Hanani, son of the seer Hanani who had earlier confronted Asa of Judah (2 Chronicles 16:7-10). The prophetic office continues across generations, a standing witness to the covenant claims of God against every king. That the oracle comes to Jehu about Baasha at all — not after Baasha's death but during his reign — confirms that prophecy in Kings functions not merely as prediction but as active covenantal prosecution: God is pressing His case in real time.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nagid* (leader, v.2) — not the ordinary word for king (*melekh*) but the term for a divinely designated leader, used of Saul (1 Samuel 9:16), David (1 Samuel 13:14), and Solomon (1 Kings 1:35). Its use here underscores the grace that preceded Baasha's apostasy: God designated him, not merely permitted him. *Ya'an asher* (inasmuch as / because, v.2) — the standard causal construction of covenantal indictment in Deuteronomy and Kings. *Kaas* (provoke to anger, v.2) — to vex or grieve; the word carries the weight of a deeply personal offense against a holy covenant partner."
